[The study mentioned in the above report and others strongly argue for the role of aerosol/ route of transmission for SARS-CoV2. There is growing evidence that in addition to contact and droplet spread, the transmission of SARS-CoV-2 via aerosols is plausible under favorable conditions, particularly in relatively confined settings with poor ventilation and long duration exposure to high concentrations of aerosols, causing the World Health Organization (WHO) and other agencies to review their guidance. Recently WHO acknowledged aerosol transmission of SARS-CoV-2, especially in closed indoor settings, and that aerosol transmission could not be ruled out from some reported outbreaks (https: //www. who.int/emergencies/diseases/novel-coronavirus-2019/question-and-answers-hub/q-a-detail/q-a-how-is-covid-19-transmitted)

Precautionary and control strategies to mitigate the possible aerosol transmission of SARS-CoV-2 should be implemented under different occasions based on risks. Settings with a large proportion of infected people or contaminated samples, such as hospitals, healthcare institutions and laboratories are the highest risk, especially to HCWs, who should be provided airborne precautions. The general public and vulnerable populations should be made aware that confined, crowded and poor ventilation environments may pose a medium risk when an infected person is present. Factoring in asymptomatic spreaders, hand hygiene, use of masks and social distancing are the key protective measures going forward in the near and foreseeable future. - Mod.UBA]

